    <h3 style="margin-top:0; color:var(--accent)">Answer Key & Marking Scheme</h3>

    <ol style="margin-left:14px; color:#1a2b3a">
      <li>
        <strong>Section A (objective) — 10 marks</strong>
        <ol>
          <li>1. B (Bones)</li>
          <li>2. B (Skull)</li>
          <li>3. B (Ball & socket joint)</li>
          <li>4. B (Spine / Vertebral column)</li>
          <li>5. D (Produce hormones) — NOT a primary function</li>
          <li>6. Femur (thigh bone)</li>
          <li>7. True</li>
          <li>8. Ligaments</li>
          <li>9. Rib (or Ribcage)</li>
          <li>10. Spine / backbone</li>
        </ol>
      </li>

      <li style="margin-top:8px">
        <strong>Section B (short answers) — sample points (2 marks each)</strong>
        <ol>
          <li>11. Joints are places where two or more bones meet. Examples: knee joint, elbow joint.</li>
          <li>12. Skull protects the brain and forms the structure of the head.</li>
          <li>13. Movable joints allow movement (e.g., knee), immovable joints do not allow movement (e.g., skull bones fused). (1 line each)</li>
          <li>14. Bones are hard because they contain minerals like calcium and phosphorus.</li>
          <li>15. Keep bones healthy: eat calcium-rich food (milk), do regular exercise, get sunlight (vitamin D).</li>
          <li>16. Arm bones: Humerus, Radius, Ulna. Leg bones: Femur, Tibia, Fibula.</li>
          <li>17. Ribcage is the set of ribs around chest protecting heart and lungs.</li>
          <li>18. Skeleton provides attachment for muscles; muscles pull on bones to create movement.</li>
        </ol>
      </li>

      <li style="margin-top:8px">
        <strong>Section C (long answers) — sample marking</strong>
        <ol>
          <li>19. Functions: support (keeps body upright), protection (protects organs), movement (works with muscles), formation of blood cells (in marrow). Award marks for three clear points + brief explanation. (6)</li>
          <li>20. Diagram: correct labelled diagram (skull, spine, ribcage, pelvis, femur) — clarity & labels. (6)</li>
          <li>21. Axial: skull, spine, ribcage (supports central axis); Appendicular: limbs and girdles (helps in movement) — give two examples each. (6)</li>
          <li>22. Care: balanced diet (calcium, protein), exercise (walking, running), sunlight (vitamin D), avoid injuries — explain why exercise strengthens bones. (6)</li>
        </ol>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </section>

